==English==
===Etymology===
Latin [[libidinosus]], from [[libido]] ‘lust’.

===Pronunciation===
*{{audio|en-us-libidinous.ogg|Audio (US)}}
*{{IPA|/lɪ'bɪdɪnəs/}}

===Adjective===
{{en-ad|libidinous}}
#Having [[lustful]] [[desires]]; characterized by [[lewdness]]; [[sensual]]; [[lascivious]].

====Quotations====
{{timeline|
1700s=1726}}
*'''1726''' — [[w:Jonathan Swift|Jonathan Swift]], ''[[s:Gulliver's Travels|Gulliver's Travels]] Part IV, ch. viii''
*:It is observed, that the red haired of both sexes are more '''libidinous''' and mischievous than the rest, whom yet they much exceed in strength and activity.

====Synonyms====
* (''having lustful desires''): [[lascivious]], [[lewd]], [[licentious]], [[lustful]], [[wanton]]

====Related terms====
*[[libidinism]]
*[[libidinist]]
*[[libidinosity]]

